WEBVTT

00:31.166 --> 00:35.833
FLAMIN' HOT

00:38.833 --> 00:41.875
<i>Call a Mexican "spicy,"
and you're playing with fire.</i>

00:42.791 --> 00:44.000
<i>But spicy?</i>

00:44.000 --> 00:46.000
<i>Yeah. See, that's how I got here.</i>

00:46.708 --> 00:48.333
<i>To this moment.</i>

00:48.333 --> 00:52.375
<i>Me, the most uneducated,
successful</i> vato <i>you'll ever meet.</i>

00:53.166 --> 00:56.708
<i>I served up my pride on a silver platter
more than once along the way.</i>

00:57.250 --> 00:59.833
<i>With my head held high,
I worked my way through kitchens,</i>

00:59.833 --> 01:03.708
<i>chicken coops, mechanic shops,
breaking a sweat to make a dollar stretch.</i>

01:05.125 --> 01:06.625
<i>Until I got here.</i>

01:07.208 --> 01:09.333
<i>See, I'm the guy
who helped bring the world</i>

01:09.333 --> 01:11.375
<i>the most popular snack it's ever seen.</i>

01:11.375 --> 01:12.541
Here you go, ma'am.

01:12.541 --> 01:14.041
<i>Nah, not that fool.</i>

01:14.750 --> 01:16.750
<i>Yeah, that fine-looking</i> guapo <i>right there,</i>

01:16.750 --> 01:19.375
<i>looking like Sean Connery
dipped in Abuelita chocolate?</i>

01:19.375 --> 01:22.916
<i>That's me.</i>
El mero mero <i>Mr. Richard Montañez.</i>

01:22.916 --> 01:25.708
<i>See, but I didn't always schmooze
with the big dogs. Nah.</i>

01:26.291 --> 01:27.541
<i>See, I started at the bottom.</i>

01:27.541 --> 01:28.625
1966

01:28.625 --> 01:32.333
<i>I mean the very bottom.
In a grape vineyard in Guasti, California.</i>

01:32.333 --> 01:33.416
GUASTI WINERY

01:34.000 --> 01:36.541
<i>Yeah, that little</i> travieso <i>right there.</i>

01:36.541 --> 01:38.500
<i>Actually, one of nine</i> traviesos<i>.</i>

01:38.500 --> 01:41.750
<i>I mean, it was the '60s. We're Mexican.
Of course my parents got down.</i>

01:41.750 --> 01:44.750
<i>See, in my mind,
I was the luckiest kid in the world</i>

01:44.750 --> 01:46.708
<i>with a playground bigger than Disneyland.</i>

01:49.500 --> 01:51.291
Get up! Why are you playing?

01:51.625 --> 01:52.625
Fill this up.

01:52.833 --> 01:54.458
Leave him alone. He's just a boy.

01:54.458 --> 01:57.416
 <i>Except my playground
was everybody else's labor camp.</i>

01:57.416 --> 01:59.041
Hey, give that to me. Go play.

01:59.041 --> 02:01.958
<i>We lived together. We worked together.</i>

02:01.958 --> 02:03.583
<i>And we survived together.</i>

02:03.583 --> 02:06.541
<i>And by the time I was ten,
I knew all I had in life was...</i>

02:06.833 --> 02:08.916
 The Montañez name.

02:09.541 --> 02:13.625
If you can show 'em what a Montañez can do

02:14.083 --> 02:16.583
they can't tell you nothin'.

02:16.875 --> 02:18.083
Don't forget that.

02:18.250 --> 02:19.083
Yes, Grandpa.

02:19.291 --> 02:21.041
I'm a Montañez!

02:21.708 --> 02:22.583
I'm a Montañez!

02:26.208 --> 02:27.416
Yes, you are.

02:29.958 --> 02:31.250
Dinner time.

02:33.458 --> 02:35.083
Leave it there, Richie.

02:35.708 --> 02:38.666
When I fix it, we're gonna call Batman.

02:42.250 --> 02:43.875
-  <i>My dad...</i>

02:43.875 --> 02:48.208
<i>...Vacho Montañez,
short for</i> Borracho<i>, 'cause, well...</i>

02:48.208 --> 02:50.666
Richard. Richard.

02:52.500 --> 02:54.166
Why are you touching my things?!

02:54.958 --> 02:57.583
Leave him alone,
he didn't do anything bad.

02:59.125 --> 03:00.750
<i>School was no better.</i>

03:01.666 --> 03:03.000
<i>Until I met Judy.</i>

03:04.708 --> 03:07.458
<i>Let's just say
us two</i> chiquillos <i>had a lot in common.</i>

03:12.041 --> 03:13.291
Hi.

03:14.208 --> 03:15.333
 Is that your lunch?

03:15.333 --> 03:16.416
Yeah.

03:16.416 --> 03:20.250
Wish it was a bologna sandwich or--
or a <i>chocolate</i>.

03:21.541 --> 03:22.583
 I got a burrito.

03:22.833 --> 03:24.166
Want some?

03:24.166 --> 03:26.666
Ew! What is that? Gross.

03:26.666 --> 03:28.000
It's a bean burrito.

03:28.000 --> 03:30.500
Ha! Figures. Beans for a dirty beaner.

03:30.500 --> 03:31.833
- Let's go, guys.

03:31.833 --> 03:34.666
<i>Judy and I knew we stuck out
like a couple of sore brown thumbs.</i>

03:34.666 --> 03:35.583
 Are you OK?

03:36.375 --> 03:38.416
<i>So we decided to stick together.</i>

03:38.416 --> 03:40.166
<i>Burritos and bullies be damned.</i>

03:41.750 --> 03:44.333
Please, make me a bologna sandwich!

03:45.666 --> 03:47.583
Nobody's making you a bologna sandwich.

03:47.583 --> 03:49.000
I don't want to be different.

03:51.375 --> 03:52.708
Here. One for you...

03:53.541 --> 03:55.333
and one for the idiot
who doesn't like burritos.

03:58.416 --> 04:00.000
Hey. There's the beaner. Ha.

04:00.000 --> 04:03.166
- He's eating it again. Gross. Look.
- Looks like it came out of a toilet.

04:03.166 --> 04:05.875
Aw, I might throw up.

04:05.875 --> 04:07.500
Oh, my God!

04:07.500 --> 04:09.541
So good!

04:09.541 --> 04:11.333
<i>Delicioso.</i>

04:11.333 --> 04:12.416
Want some?

04:12.416 --> 04:14.583
Ew, I'm not gonna eat that!

04:14.583 --> 04:15.666
You eat it.

04:15.666 --> 04:17.000
- I dare you.

04:24.875 --> 04:27.541
- Hey, this is pretty good.
-  I want some. Give me one.

04:27.541 --> 04:29.000
Me first. Give me this one.

04:31.916 --> 04:33.083
Twenty-five cents.

04:36.750 --> 04:37.750
Let's go.

04:37.750 --> 04:41.833
<i>And just like that, I became
the burrito hustler of Guasti Elementary.</i>

04:42.958 --> 04:45.333
<i>Ever heard of a little thing called
"supply and demand"?</i>

04:46.500 --> 04:48.833
-  Whoa! I want one.

04:48.833 --> 04:51.500
<i>Man, Taco Bell didn't introduce
the world to burritos.</i>

04:51.500 --> 04:53.000
<i>Me and my mama did.</i>

04:53.500 --> 04:55.625
<i>Well, at least
that's what it felt like to me.</i>

05:00.291 --> 05:04.083
<i>I wasn't gonna let another day go by
where Judy ate a sad sack lunch.</i>

05:04.583 --> 05:05.750
HERSHEY'S
MILK CHOCOLATE

05:05.750 --> 05:08.208
<i>My Jude wanted chocolate,
and she was gonna get it.</i>

05:09.916 --> 05:11.208
You better have money for that.

05:15.208 --> 05:17.416
Where'd you steal that from, huh, boy?

05:20.000 --> 05:22.041
<i>Here's how this</i> bronca <i>could've gone.</i>

05:22.041 --> 05:23.625
Gee, mister!

05:23.625 --> 05:25.875
I made that money on my newspaper route.

05:25.875 --> 05:29.375
No funny business here.
Just a kid with a girl to impress.

05:29.375 --> 05:32.333
Well, look at this fine,
upstanding young citizen here, huh?

05:33.416 --> 05:35.250
- Wow!
-  Huh?

05:35.250 --> 05:37.166
You go get that girl, son.

05:37.166 --> 05:39.166
And you know what?
Have some free candy on the house.

05:39.166 --> 05:41.291
- Ooh.

05:41.291 --> 05:42.500
Ah, good-looking kid.

05:42.500 --> 05:44.041
- Yeah, smart too.
- Yeah.

05:45.916 --> 05:47.791
<i>But I wasn't a white kid.</i>

05:48.375 --> 05:49.375
<i>I was brown.</i>

05:52.916 --> 05:54.083
Get in.

05:56.833 --> 06:00.625
<i>And when the world treats
you like a criminal, you become one.</i>

06:00.625 --> 06:01.708
1974

06:05.833 --> 06:09.958
<i>Yeah! That's that</i> firme pachuco
<i>steez everyone was wearing in the '70s.</i>

06:09.958 --> 06:11.958
<i>I look good!</i>

06:11.958 --> 06:14.458
<i>Now, before you start talking smack about</i>

06:14.458 --> 06:16.958
<i>"why Mexicans always
got to be gangsters," don't.</i>

06:16.958 --> 06:18.916
<i>'Cause I didn't make this up. I lived it.</i>

06:18.916 --> 06:21.500
<i>You see, back then,</i>
la policía <i>believed they had the right...</i>

06:21.500 --> 06:22.500
SToP KiLLiNG US

06:22.500 --> 06:25.041
<i>...to beat your ass in the street
if your name was González or Martínez.</i>

06:25.041 --> 06:26.041
BE BROWN & BE PROUD

06:26.041 --> 06:27.666
<i>To be Chicano meant being invisible...</i>

06:27.666 --> 06:28.708
WE WILL NOT BE INTIMIDATED!

06:28.708 --> 06:30.250
<i>...but still getting a beatdown.</i>

06:30.250 --> 06:32.375
<i>And if</i> la jura <i>wasn't beating your ass,</i>

06:32.375 --> 06:35.500
<i>you were getting shipped off to war
to drop like flies.</i>

06:38.916 --> 06:40.833
<i>I was just trying to survive.</i>

06:40.833 --> 06:42.125
<i>And Judy?</i>

06:42.125 --> 06:43.875
<i>She was surviving too.</i>

06:44.666 --> 06:46.708
<i>And we were real good at surviving.</i>

06:46.708 --> 06:48.166
<i>Together.</i>

06:51.416 --> 06:53.708
<i>The Chicano Movement was in full effect,</i>

06:53.708 --> 06:55.541
<i>but I wasn't paying attention.</i>

06:55.541 --> 06:57.708
<i>I had family business to attend to.</i>

06:59.791 --> 07:03.333
<i>You see, my homeys were
the only family I knew, you dig?</i>

07:03.916 --> 07:05.750
<i>We always had each other's backs.</i>

07:06.416 --> 07:07.958
Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey!

07:08.916 --> 07:10.750
- Don't be pushing my man!

07:12.375 --> 07:13.583
Get her, Judy!

07:14.500 --> 07:15.833
<i>Business was good.</i>

07:16.958 --> 07:18.541
<i>And I was living the life.</i>

07:21.041 --> 07:22.208
2-hour home test for pregnancy

07:22.208 --> 07:26.625
<i>But ignorance is bliss
until one of you wakes up.</i>

07:27.208 --> 07:28.875
Rich, you gotta change now.

07:28.875 --> 07:31.250
- For us and for the baby.
- What you talking about?

07:31.250 --> 07:33.291
- Check out this new ride I got us.
- Yeah, exactly!

07:33.291 --> 07:34.750
Like, where did this car come from?

07:37.916 --> 07:41.083
Rich, if I am sitting in a stolen car,
I swear--

07:41.083 --> 07:42.375
It's on a layaway plan.

07:42.958 --> 07:44.708
- Are you kidding me right now?

07:44.708 --> 07:47.041
Why do you keep doing stuff like this
all the time?

07:49.250 --> 07:50.458
Look at me, son.

07:50.958 --> 07:54.000
You're not worthless, Richard.
Do you hear me?

07:54.000 --> 07:55.666
You're not stupid.

07:55.666 --> 07:59.208
You've got a brain between those ears,
not just that dumb mustache.

07:59.208 --> 08:03.083
You're not your father,
but you will be if you don't change.

08:03.833 --> 08:07.541
If you don't wake up, you're gonna
end up in a cell or in the ground.

08:07.541 --> 08:09.625
We can't lose you, Rich.

08:09.625 --> 08:11.291
And I think you can do better.

08:15.375 --> 08:18.250
<i>Man, it's a miracle
he didn't throw the book at me.</i>

08:18.250 --> 08:21.083
Hey, yo, Richie! Richie!

08:21.666 --> 08:22.750
Hey, <i>vato</i>!

08:23.583 --> 08:24.583
You ready to leave?

08:24.583 --> 08:26.083
Let's go, homey!

08:29.208 --> 08:30.791
Let's go!

08:36.625 --> 08:38.541
<i>You see, life is about choices.</i>

08:40.291 --> 08:41.375
<i>Big ones.</i>

08:47.333 --> 08:49.583
<i>It was time for me
to choose something better.</i>

08:50.166 --> 08:51.166
1982

08:51.166 --> 08:52.958
<i>But better doesn't always mean easier.</i>

08:52.958 --> 08:55.041
We can't fix that right now.
We don't have time.

08:55.041 --> 08:56.791
-  This thing's stuck.

08:56.791 --> 08:58.666
This wire is corroded.
What the hell?

08:58.666 --> 09:01.166
Yes, <i>amor</i>. Are you hungry?

09:03.833 --> 09:07.041
<i>Amá. Amá</i>, look.

09:08.750 --> 09:10.250
I know, baby. I know.

09:12.708 --> 09:13.833
Here. Chew.

09:15.833 --> 09:17.666
You gotta hurry up, baby.
We're gonna be late.

09:17.666 --> 09:18.791
Yeah, yeah.

09:18.791 --> 09:20.375
- How the heck...
- Spit.

09:20.958 --> 09:22.833
- Put your leg up.
-  I think I got it.

09:22.833 --> 09:24.375
Okay, I think I got it.

09:24.875 --> 09:27.250
All right, go. Go wait in the <i>sala</i>.

09:30.916 --> 09:33.125
Yes, Mexicans can!

09:33.125 --> 09:34.708
I fixed it.

09:36.875 --> 09:38.583
Baby, that sounded really bad.

09:38.583 --> 09:41.916
Bad? Nah.
No, the fridge is just taking a nap.

09:41.916 --> 09:44.458
- The food is gonna spoil. Come on.
- The food will be fine.

09:44.458 --> 09:45.708
What are we gonna do?

09:45.708 --> 09:47.375
- When are we gonna have time to fix it?
- Hey.

09:47.375 --> 09:49.208
- We can't afford another.
- Look at me.

09:49.208 --> 09:50.666
- What are we gonna do?
- Breathe.

09:52.083 --> 09:53.541
Three.

09:54.333 --> 09:56.041
Two.

09:57.125 --> 09:58.541
One.

09:59.125 --> 10:00.708
-  Breathe.
- Breathe.

10:02.833 --> 10:04.416
Someone's gonna say "yes" today.

10:05.250 --> 10:06.250
Yeah.

10:06.250 --> 10:07.708
I got this.

10:07.708 --> 10:09.000
<i>And I did have this.</i>

10:09.000 --> 10:12.125
-<i>Judy even made me a fancy résumé.</i>
- Excuse me. Hey, man. How are you?

10:12.125 --> 10:14.708
<i>'Cause who's gonna say "no" to something
that sounds so French?</i>

10:14.708 --> 10:17.000
- We don't got no work, bro.
- Now, I can mow lawns.

10:17.000 --> 10:19.500
I can hedge the bushes.
I'll clean out the equipment.

10:19.500 --> 10:21.958
- Whatever you need.
- Sorry, man. My crew's full.

10:22.541 --> 10:25.291
Here's my number. Just call me anytime
if something opens up.

10:25.291 --> 10:27.750
Excuse me.
Do you know where they might be hiring?

10:28.416 --> 10:30.083
My father and grandfather
were farmworkers.

10:30.083 --> 10:33.416
I was too when I was a kid so,
I-- I remember well.

10:33.416 --> 10:35.041
If you could just take my résumé.

10:36.000 --> 10:38.125
-  No, thanks.

10:38.833 --> 10:40.708
-  No, thank you.

10:40.708 --> 10:41.958
Here's my résumé.

10:42.458 --> 10:44.750
And I'll do anything.
I'll wash dishes. Whatever.

10:44.750 --> 10:46.125
Don't hold your breath.

10:46.708 --> 10:48.916
- There you go.

10:53.625 --> 10:56.458
Some people call it juvie.
I call it summer camp.

10:58.083 --> 11:00.166
Dos Manos MOVERS - Help WANTED

11:01.750 --> 11:05.041
Who needs a high school diploma
to stack a bunch of junk? Am I right?

11:07.250 --> 11:08.875
We ain't hiring.

11:08.875 --> 11:12.500
You just don't look like the kind of guy
who's got an ounce of initiative.

11:12.500 --> 11:14.333
What kind of guy does that look like?

11:15.250 --> 11:17.083
Hey, hey, hey! Hey! That's my car.

11:17.083 --> 11:20.250
Don't do that! You have respect
for other people's property, dang it!

11:20.250 --> 11:21.291
Hey, hey, hey!

11:21.291 --> 11:23.625
- You understand me?
- Get your hands off my kid!

11:23.625 --> 11:25.083
Don't be talking to him like that.

11:25.083 --> 11:28.791
Good Lord! You women pump
these wetbacks out like a factory.

11:28.791 --> 11:32.125
- What did you just say?
- Hey! Hey! You touch my kid?

11:32.125 --> 11:34.000
- Leave it, Rich.
- What do you mean, "leave it"?

11:34.000 --> 11:36.500
Yes, leave it! The police will come,
and that's not good for us.

11:36.500 --> 11:37.916
Mommy?

11:37.916 --> 11:39.583
What's a wetback?

11:41.375 --> 11:43.625
It's okay, baby.
You didn't do anything wrong.

11:43.625 --> 11:45.291
- Okay.

11:46.166 --> 11:48.083
- I know.

11:50.916 --> 11:52.541
We need to go in at some point, babe.

11:54.416 --> 11:55.458
I really don't want to.

11:55.458 --> 11:56.625
The kids need to eat.

11:56.625 --> 11:59.250
- We have food at home.
- No, we don't.

11:59.250 --> 12:01.625
The fridge just broke. We don't have work.

12:01.625 --> 12:03.125
You think I don't know that?

12:05.208 --> 12:08.083
Tortillas can't pay the bills,
and our kids have shoes that talk.

12:08.083 --> 12:09.208
We need help.

12:10.291 --> 12:13.041
Please just suck it up,
and let's go into Vacho's.

12:21.666 --> 12:23.750
Can't your sister get you more shifts
at the store?

12:24.333 --> 12:26.083
She tried ama, but there's no more shifts.

12:26.208 --> 12:27.125
 You know what?

12:27.625 --> 12:29.833
It's not your job
to provide for your family.

12:31.166 --> 12:32.625
It's this <i>menso</i>'s job.

12:33.583 --> 12:35.166
What's the matter with you, huh?

12:35.166 --> 12:37.000
Letting your woman work so much.

12:37.708 --> 12:40.541
If you'd read the Bible, you'd know it's
a man's job to provide for his family.

12:40.541 --> 12:42.041
<i>You heard that right. God.</i>

12:42.041 --> 12:44.500
<i>Vacho got saved about five years ago.</i>

12:44.500 --> 12:47.083
<i>He replaced the gin and juice
with some Jesus juice.</i>

12:47.833 --> 12:50.458
You need to set an example for your kid.
Ain't that right, <i>mijo</i>?

12:51.458 --> 12:53.708
He looked for work today, didn't you mijo?

12:53.708 --> 12:56.750
Yes. We both have. There's
just no work for anybody right now.

12:56.750 --> 12:59.416
Oh, there's work out there.
There's always work out there.

13:00.041 --> 13:02.833
Problem is, all they see is a good-
for-nothing gangster when they see you.

13:02.833 --> 13:05.166
- Mm-hmm.
- If you gave your life to the Lord,

13:05.166 --> 13:07.208
you would see how fast
the help would come, <i>mijo</i>.

13:07.208 --> 13:10.875
Well, last time I checked, Jesus was poor,
<i>prieto</i> and powerless like me.

13:11.500 --> 13:13.333
And he did some pretty gangster shit.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.250
You wanna be a good husband
and father or what, <i>huevón</i>?

13:17.708 --> 13:20.250
Light this and say a prayer. It'll help.

13:20.250 --> 13:22.875
<i>Ya, Concha.</i>
Stop it with the candle, huh?

13:23.750 --> 13:25.791
- Ain't no candle gonna fix him.
-  Okay, Vacho.

13:25.791 --> 13:27.125
He needs to fix himself.

13:27.125 --> 13:29.833
Thank you, Concha. At this point,
I'll put my faith in anything.

13:29.833 --> 13:33.250
How about you forget about the stupid
candle and have a little faith in me, huh?

13:33.250 --> 13:34.750
Rich, are you serious?

13:46.083 --> 13:48.166
<i>It felt like I had no choice.</i>

13:48.875 --> 13:50.916
<i>I had to go back to what I knew best.</i>

13:52.333 --> 13:56.708
<i>And if I wanted to start selling again,
I had to check in with the old crew.</i>

14:11.666 --> 14:13.875
<i>Órale.</i> What's up, homeboy?

14:13.875 --> 14:16.166
-  What's up?
- It's the big dog.

14:17.041 --> 14:19.166
You finally back for more business, <i>ese</i>?

14:19.166 --> 14:20.541
Depends.

14:20.541 --> 14:21.458
Oh, yeah?

14:21.458 --> 14:23.166
Oh, shit, Richard's back?

14:23.166 --> 14:25.458
- 'Sup? <i>Órale.</i>
- I got you, homey.

14:26.833 --> 14:28.583
Hey, check it out.

14:28.583 --> 14:31.208
This <i>vato</i> right here
could sell water to a whale, <i>carnal</i>.

14:31.208 --> 14:33.166
The baddest salesman on the block, homey.

14:33.166 --> 14:34.333
Nah.

14:35.833 --> 14:37.083
Richard's good.

14:39.416 --> 14:41.125
<i>Every hood has a big brother.</i>

14:41.125 --> 14:42.458
<i>The jefe.</i>

14:42.458 --> 14:44.583
<i>The</i> vato <i>who runs everything on the block.</i>

14:45.208 --> 14:47.333
<i>That was Tony Romero.</i>

14:47.333 --> 14:49.125
Listen, Tony, I know what I'm doing.

14:49.125 --> 14:51.625
No, you don't. 'Cause you got babies.

14:51.625 --> 14:53.250
You don't need to sling nothing.

14:53.250 --> 14:55.416
Hey, man,
if he wants to deal, let him deal.

14:55.416 --> 14:58.083
Yeah, homes,
we don't all got fancy factory jobs

14:58.083 --> 14:59.958
with benefits and stupid hairnets.

14:59.958 --> 15:02.208
Frito factory.

15:02.708 --> 15:04.541
- You working at Frito-Lay?
-  Yeah.

15:05.458 --> 15:06.541
So, what?

15:07.291 --> 15:09.500
- Well, hook me up with a job.
-  This fool.

15:09.500 --> 15:11.583
- What?

15:11.583 --> 15:14.000
They hired this Mexican
Hulk-Hogan-looking <i>pendejo</i>.

15:14.000 --> 15:15.083
Why not me?

15:15.083 --> 15:17.375
<i>Este vato</i>, man.

15:19.500 --> 15:21.708
You really wanna do this, punk? Huh?

15:21.708 --> 15:23.833
I'm gonna give you
a <i>putazo en la madre</i>, fool.

15:23.833 --> 15:25.333
Tony, I just need a job, man.

15:27.958 --> 15:29.208
Go get an application.

15:29.208 --> 15:30.291
Who's stopping you?

15:31.166 --> 15:32.791
Just put in a good word.

15:34.041 --> 15:35.875
Like you said, I got kids.

15:41.833 --> 15:43.166
I'll see what I can do.

15:53.583 --> 15:55.750
Hey,
forget about that dude at the store, <i>mijo</i>.

15:55.750 --> 15:57.958
You know you're a good kid, right?

15:57.958 --> 15:59.291
Yeah, I know.

16:00.166 --> 16:01.583
Let's check it out.

16:01.583 --> 16:02.916
Put your arm out.

16:05.208 --> 16:06.666
This?

16:07.333 --> 16:08.416
We're the same.

16:09.625 --> 16:12.083
If I'm good, you're good.

16:13.875 --> 16:15.791
No matter what anybody says.

16:15.791 --> 16:17.125
Understand?

16:18.458 --> 16:20.416
Can we just watch TV, <i>Apá</i>?

16:21.583 --> 16:22.625
Sure, <i>mijo</i>.

16:23.125 --> 16:26.541
<i>There's a reason why
poor people always talking about God.</i>

16:26.541 --> 16:28.208
<i>'Cause when you don't got nothing,</i>

16:28.208 --> 16:32.291
<i>the guy promising you everything
starts to sound pretty good.</i>

16:32.291 --> 16:33.875
Frito Lay

16:36.000 --> 16:37.500
Frito Lay

16:45.958 --> 16:47.583
Excuse me. Sorry.

16:47.583 --> 16:49.125
Um, hi.

16:49.125 --> 16:52.041
Um, my name is Richard Montañez.
I'm coming to bring a résumé.

16:52.041 --> 16:54.416
We don't take résumés.
You have to fill out an application.

16:54.416 --> 16:56.875
And before you ask, no,
we don't have it in Spanish.

17:00.333 --> 17:01.333
Okay, thanks.

17:08.458 --> 17:10.750
Frito Lay - PEPSICO
APPLICATION FOR EMPLOYMENT

17:22.083 --> 17:24.333
PLEASE READ EACH STATEMENT
CAREFULLY BEFORE SIGNING

17:30.333 --> 17:31.833
Here's my application.

17:37.958 --> 17:40.708
EDUCATION - Have you received
a high school diploma or its equivalent?

17:44.625 --> 17:48.833
Hi, um, you think it'd be okay
if I brought this back later?

17:49.416 --> 17:50.916
Probably a good idea, hon.

17:53.666 --> 17:54.875
Thank you.

17:54.875 --> 17:56.166
Pen.

17:56.166 --> 17:58.750
Oh. Sorry.

17:59.333 --> 18:00.541
Baby!

18:00.541 --> 18:01.833
Sofía got fired.

18:01.833 --> 18:04.625
Because she was fooling around, yet again.

18:04.625 --> 18:08.083
So, guess who gets all
of her shifts at the store? This girl!

18:08.083 --> 18:12.500
So, I got us
the name-brand cornflakes to celebrate.

18:15.500 --> 18:17.083
Hey, what's wrong?

18:17.750 --> 18:19.208
Baby, what's "initiative" mean?

18:19.208 --> 18:23.750
It means, uh, s-someone who can
take charge without being asked. Why?

18:24.583 --> 18:26.458
Do I look like a guy who's got initiative?

18:27.958 --> 18:29.625
What is it? Tell me.

18:31.166 --> 18:32.666
High school diploma.

18:34.416 --> 18:35.958
You're applying to Frito-Lay?

18:35.958 --> 18:37.708
Yeah, but I got to be
a high school graduate,

18:37.708 --> 18:39.166
and I can barely read the application.

18:39.166 --> 18:41.416
No, baby, that's okay. I'll help you.

18:43.750 --> 18:45.750
I need my wife to help me
fill out the application.

18:45.750 --> 18:46.958
God, what an idiot.

18:46.958 --> 18:48.750
Hey! Stop it.

18:48.750 --> 18:50.583
Screw the diploma. Can you do the job?

18:50.583 --> 18:52.125
Yeah, I think so.

18:53.166 --> 18:54.166
Can you?

18:54.750 --> 18:56.125
Yes, I can.

18:56.125 --> 18:58.541
Okay, well, guess what?

18:58.541 --> 19:02.291
You graduated
from San Bernardino High School.

19:02.916 --> 19:04.291
Class of '71.

19:04.291 --> 19:05.625
Yeah?

19:05.625 --> 19:07.500
With honors. What's up?

19:07.500 --> 19:09.500
Okay, <i>papi</i>, let's not get crazy.

19:09.500 --> 19:11.333
Come on. They ain't gonna know.

19:14.916 --> 19:18.041
So, Tony says you're a good guy.

19:18.041 --> 19:19.125
Yeah, I hope so.

19:22.833 --> 19:24.166
You fill this out?

19:24.666 --> 19:25.791
Yeah.

19:26.375 --> 19:27.583
You write like a girl.

19:28.583 --> 19:29.583
Thank you.

19:29.583 --> 19:32.000
San Bernardino High, huh? I went there.

19:32.625 --> 19:33.625
You did?

19:33.625 --> 19:35.708
Remember Principal Grimaldi?

19:35.708 --> 19:37.125
Tough. Annoying.

19:37.125 --> 19:38.875
Heck, yeah, man.

19:38.875 --> 19:40.666
I hated that guy.

19:41.250 --> 19:43.333
Principal Grimaldi is a woman.

19:44.958 --> 19:47.041
Yea-Yeah, but she was like--

19:47.041 --> 19:50.625
She was like-- like a woman
who felt like one of the guys.

19:51.416 --> 19:52.458
Okay.

19:53.041 --> 19:55.208
- All right.
- Look, um, sir!

19:55.208 --> 19:57.500
Look, I'm fast. I'm smart.

19:57.500 --> 19:59.458
I-- I know I don't look it,

19:59.458 --> 20:01.916
but I promise
I'll be the best worker you ever hired.

20:01.916 --> 20:05.375
Look, maybe I don't got no diploma,
but I got a PhD.

20:05.375 --> 20:08.791
- Hmm?
- I'm poor, hungry and determined, sir.

20:10.250 --> 20:12.250
Oh, well, that's just stupid.

20:14.583 --> 20:15.833
Fine.

20:15.833 --> 20:18.250
Honestly, most of the Mexicans here
work pretty dang hard.

20:18.250 --> 20:21.375
It's a janitor gig. What's the worst
you could do? Break a mop?

20:21.375 --> 20:22.458
But I won't.

20:25.125 --> 20:26.708
<i>For the first time in years...</i>

20:26.708 --> 20:27.791
Montanez

20:27.791 --> 20:29.833
<i>...this</i> chavo <i>had a legit grown-up job.</i>

20:30.333 --> 20:31.666
<i>See, fools were jealous.</i>

20:31.666 --> 20:33.666
<i>Shoot, I was jealous of me.</i>

20:35.875 --> 20:37.375
Frito Lay - Montanez

20:44.458 --> 20:48.333
All right, you punch in on time.
You punch out on time. No exceptions.

20:48.333 --> 20:49.666
This here is the main pit.

20:49.666 --> 20:52.708
Cornmeal goes in that extruder,
through the oven.

20:52.708 --> 20:55.916
Chips cool down in this tumbler.
Lots of grease. You'll be scrubbing that.

20:55.916 --> 20:57.333
Right there are the fryers.

20:57.333 --> 20:59.458
You're gonna change the oil
on those every two days.

20:59.458 --> 21:01.458
Make sure you scrub the exterior too

21:01.458 --> 21:04.458
because it'll drip like a son of a gun
and muck up the floors.

21:04.458 --> 21:06.000
Could cause a lawsuit.

21:06.833 --> 21:09.000
And I don't need
a stinking lawsuit, got it?

21:09.000 --> 21:10.583
This here is the main walkway.

21:10.583 --> 21:14.458
Lot of forklifts
and traffic moving around, so be careful.

21:14.458 --> 21:17.208
<i>It was crazy.
Like a city of machines.</i>

21:17.208 --> 21:19.375
<i>It was</i> firme<i>.</i>

21:20.458 --> 21:23.125
<i>This</i> moreno <i>was finally part of something.</i>

21:23.125 --> 21:24.583
<i>Something big.</i>

21:24.583 --> 21:27.250
Here the chips are sorted,
weighed and bagged.

21:27.250 --> 21:30.708
Underneath there, those conveyors,
I want you to scrub right up under that.

21:30.708 --> 21:33.833
These bins are gonna wanna be
emptied out every hour.

21:33.833 --> 21:36.666
Main trash bin is outside there
on the loading dock.

21:36.666 --> 21:39.166
But, basically, don't get in anyone's way.

21:41.500 --> 21:44.583
Montañez! Hey, you "comprende-ing"?

21:44.583 --> 21:46.083
Yes, sir!

21:46.083 --> 21:49.791
Cornmeal shooter, oil lawsuits,
every bin, every hour.

21:49.791 --> 21:51.333
I'll be the best dumper you ever had.

21:51.333 --> 21:54.208
Okay, I can see
you're gonna be a weird one.

21:54.208 --> 21:56.916
All right, this here is Nacho.
Nacho. Richard.

21:56.916 --> 21:59.083
Nacho will fill you in on anything
I didn't explain.

21:59.083 --> 22:00.791
- Good luck.
- What do you need help with?

22:00.791 --> 22:03.916
<i>Packaging operator,
you're needed on the floor, please.</i>

22:03.916 --> 22:06.000
<i>Packaging operator,
you're needed on the floor.</i>

22:06.000 --> 22:07.083
Wow!

22:07.625 --> 22:09.458
Hey, this is so cool. Have you seen this?

22:13.833 --> 22:15.750
 Calm down, Rich. Easy.

22:17.875 --> 22:19.208
Hey!

22:20.500 --> 22:22.125
I got you. That's too heavy for you, <i>vato</i>.

22:22.125 --> 22:24.916
-  <i>Gracias. Gracias.</i>
-  All right.

22:29.000 --> 22:30.916
<i>Amá</i>, Dad's home!

22:30.916 --> 22:34.666
Oh, my gosh! Baby, how did it go?
Did they like you? I was praying all day.

22:34.666 --> 22:37.333
<i>Apá</i>, they gave you free Cheetos?

22:37.333 --> 22:39.708
You know white people
don't give you no free nothing.

22:40.208 --> 22:42.041
Plus...

22:42.708 --> 22:45.708
-  What we got, babe?
-<i>Arroz con quesadillas.</i>

22:45.708 --> 22:46.791
Mmm.

22:46.791 --> 22:49.541
We always eat the same thing.

22:49.541 --> 22:52.833
Hey! You like my quesadillas. Here. Eat.

22:53.333 --> 22:54.666
Hey.

22:55.625 --> 22:58.000
-  You proud of your man?
- Maybe.

22:58.000 --> 23:00.166
Start bringing home free food,
and I'll think about it.

23:00.166 --> 23:02.125
-<i>Chale.</i>

23:04.625 --> 23:07.583
Babe, you got that candle burning 24-7.
You're gonna burn down the house.

23:07.583 --> 23:10.333
Hey! What are you doing?
So, you trying to get fired?

23:10.333 --> 23:11.750
- I don't think so.

23:11.750 --> 23:14.041
-  Brat. Stop it.
- What? It's so windy in here.

23:14.041 --> 23:15.875
-  I'm gonna get you!

23:15.875 --> 23:18.083
- Stop it!
- I won't do it.

23:18.083 --> 23:19.333
TIME CLOCK

23:33.958 --> 23:34.958
Hey, that was fun, man.

23:34.958 --> 23:38.458
I've never used a power washer before.
I didn't know they could clean like that.

23:38.458 --> 23:41.166
You know what? I think if we used vinegar,
it would do really well.

23:41.166 --> 23:42.708
Vin-- Judy has this-- You know what?

23:42.708 --> 23:44.750
I think she used baking soda.
That's what it is.

23:50.791 --> 23:52.000
Oh, hey!

23:52.000 --> 23:54.750
So, you're telling me
that the cornmeal mixes with the water,

23:54.750 --> 23:57.333
goes into that machine, is like, "Poof!"

23:57.333 --> 23:59.041
Comes out shaped like a Cheeto?

24:01.458 --> 24:02.875
But, like, how?

24:02.875 --> 24:04.166
Is it, um--

24:05.083 --> 24:06.541
Is it the heat plus the pressure?

24:08.083 --> 24:11.000
Don't you got a mop to flirt with
instead of me, Paco?

24:11.583 --> 24:13.666
-  <i>Man, I know guys like this.</i>
- Okay.

24:13.666 --> 24:15.375
<i>I've dealt with them my whole life.</i>

24:16.875 --> 24:19.708
-  Oh, yeah, Richard! Yeah!

24:19.708 --> 24:21.708
-  <i>Nah, just kidding.</i>

24:22.833 --> 24:25.416
<i>What'd you think?
This is my first week on the job.</i>

24:25.416 --> 24:27.000
<i>I had to mind my gangster.</i>

24:33.041 --> 24:35.083
Yeah, it's the heat plus the pressure.

24:38.041 --> 24:40.000
Collets look good to you, Baker?

24:40.958 --> 24:41.958
Yeah.

24:44.625 --> 24:47.625
Is that what they call the "temp levels,"
or is that part of the machine?

24:47.625 --> 24:50.333
Nah, man. The doodles, bro.
The Cheeto doodles are the collets.

24:50.916 --> 24:53.041
Oh, nice.
Hey, it's wild, isn't it?

24:53.041 --> 24:55.500
How all these gauges and gadgets
make a bunch of doodles.

24:55.500 --> 24:56.583
Montañez!

24:57.333 --> 25:00.500
Come on. The extruder's caked
in cheese dust. Clean it out!

25:00.500 --> 25:02.708
It's Montañez, sir!

25:08.583 --> 25:09.833
You got a cool job, brother!

25:11.750 --> 25:13.666
Yes, I do, brother.

25:13.666 --> 25:15.166
I'm an engineer.

25:15.708 --> 25:16.708
Self-made.

25:16.708 --> 25:18.000
For real?

25:18.000 --> 25:19.083
For real.

25:20.166 --> 25:21.166
Hey, hold up!

25:35.583 --> 25:37.708
You push all them buttons
like you're a superhero.

25:37.708 --> 25:39.291
Like pa-pa-pow!

25:41.458 --> 25:42.666
Hey, I'm Richard.

25:42.666 --> 25:43.833
Richard Montañez.

25:46.583 --> 25:47.583
Clarence C. Baker.

25:47.583 --> 25:49.000
<i>Órale.</i>

25:49.000 --> 25:51.208
- Pleasure to meet you, <i>hermano</i>.
- Mm-hmm.

25:51.208 --> 25:52.541
Hey, what's the "C" stand for?

25:53.125 --> 25:54.416
Charisma.

25:55.000 --> 25:56.000
Oh, okay.

25:59.916 --> 26:01.541
Hey, I got a question.

26:01.541 --> 26:03.541
You think there might be a way
that I can look at--

26:03.541 --> 26:05.166
Man, I don't even know what it's called.

26:05.166 --> 26:07.875
It's, like, a diorama
or a diagram of this machine.

26:07.875 --> 26:10.458
Now, why would you wanna learn
about a machine I run, boy?

26:11.166 --> 26:13.583
Hey, hey, hey, hey. Uh, my bad, Clarence.

26:13.583 --> 26:16.666
The janitor got a little lost.
He was just looking for the cafeteria.

26:16.666 --> 26:19.000
- Just come on.
-  I was just talking to him, man.

26:19.000 --> 26:22.000
Richie, don't be talking
to people like that, homey.

26:22.000 --> 26:23.791
This here's like high school, <i>menso</i>.

26:23.791 --> 26:26.000
The mean guys
ain't trying to talk to no janitor.

26:26.000 --> 26:28.458
I never been to high school.
I don't know what you're talking about.

26:28.458 --> 26:29.875
-  Come on, man.

26:29.875 --> 26:31.500
New guy's already messing up?

26:31.500 --> 26:33.791
Oh, yeah! He's talking to Clarence
like he knows the guy.

26:33.791 --> 26:36.916
- You already met Nacho. This is Hector.
- Hey.

26:36.916 --> 26:38.291
- That's Alejandro.
- How you guys doing?

26:38.291 --> 26:40.666
-  Pass me the salsa, yeah.

26:41.250 --> 26:42.291
 Can I have one?

26:42.416 --> 26:44.541
I don't like the green one, bro. <i>Gracias.</i>

26:44.541 --> 26:47.291
-  You're gonna eat it all.
- The meat doesn't taste like anything.

26:47.875 --> 26:50.375
Here's what you need to know
if you're gonna survive around here.

26:50.375 --> 26:53.458
The guys at that table,
those are the plant managers.

26:53.458 --> 26:55.833
Calm, confident.

26:55.833 --> 26:58.708
They got white picket fences and 401(k)s.

26:58.708 --> 27:00.791
<i>They got money, champagne,</i>

27:00.791 --> 27:04.583
<i>and no worries
because they got the cushy, safe jobs.</i>

27:04.583 --> 27:06.708
<i>Then, there's the floor managers.</i>

27:06.708 --> 27:10.916
<i>They ain't got no job security,
but they got all the responsibility.</i>

27:10.916 --> 27:12.291
- God dang it!

27:12.291 --> 27:14.500
<i>Poor bastards are bitter
because they gotta answer</i>

27:14.500 --> 27:17.333
<i>to the guys above them
who do less and make more.</i>

27:17.333 --> 27:20.416
Y luego<i>, the machine operators.</i>

27:20.416 --> 27:23.916
<i>Blue-collar but proud.
They get everybody's respect.</i>

27:23.916 --> 27:26.708
<i>And Clarence, he's the best of them all.</i>

27:26.708 --> 27:28.791
<i>Homey's been here longer than anybody.</i>

27:29.208 --> 27:31.125
 Poor guy. So hardworking.

27:31.375 --> 27:32.916
Yeah, but why is that bad?

27:32.916 --> 27:35.583
'Cause the <i>compa</i> has been trying
to get from that table

27:35.583 --> 27:39.083
to that table for 15 years.

27:39.083 --> 27:42.083
Half those <i>cabrónes</i> at the top learned
everything they know from Clarence.

27:42.083 --> 27:44.916
There's a reason he doesn't like
getting questions about his machines.

27:44.916 --> 27:47.458
-<i>Exacto.</i>
- And then, you got us.

27:48.166 --> 27:49.666
Lowest of the low.

27:49.666 --> 27:53.625
- The assembly line, packing--
-  Speak for yourself, homey.

27:53.625 --> 27:55.416
Us drivers are elite status.

27:55.583 --> 27:58.333
 Shut up, Mr. Clean!

27:58.333 --> 28:00.000
Ooh! <i>Ay, güey. Órale.</i>

28:00.000 --> 28:01.583
And then there's you two.

28:01.583 --> 28:03.875
- Bottom-feeders. The janitors.

28:04.125 --> 28:05.458
 I'm not a bottom feeder.

28:05.583 --> 28:08.500
Guys like you can't be
talking to a guy like Clarence.

28:09.125 --> 28:10.833
'Cause we don't break rank around here.

28:10.833 --> 28:12.000
<i>Entiendes?</i>

28:12.000 --> 28:13.166
It's about respect.

28:13.166 --> 28:15.583
And guys like you and me,
we don't get shots like this.

28:15.583 --> 28:16.666
So don't blow it.

28:16.666 --> 28:19.333
'Cause I'm not going back
to that life, <i>carnal</i>.

28:19.333 --> 28:20.666
Are you?

28:29.250 --> 28:30.375
You should see the machines.

28:30.375 --> 28:32.750
Oh, and I got my own little office
<i>y todo, Amá</i>.

28:32.750 --> 28:34.041
 That's nice, mijo.

28:35.750 --> 28:38.750
An office, huh?
You mean more like a closet, <i>que no</i>?

28:39.375 --> 28:41.166
Where you stuff the cleaning supplies.

28:41.166 --> 28:42.750
Man, it ain't no closet.

28:43.458 --> 28:45.791
Nacho and I share a desk in there.
We got a phone and everything.

28:45.791 --> 28:47.833
Ah, still a dead end, <i>sangrón</i>.

28:47.833 --> 28:49.166
It's a job.

28:49.166 --> 28:50.666
Provide for my family.

28:50.666 --> 28:51.750
Yeah, for how long?

28:53.291 --> 28:54.791
Until you change your insides,

28:54.791 --> 28:56.458
you're gonna keep
making the same mistakes.

28:56.458 --> 28:58.500
You can't spend
the rest of your life scrubbing floors

28:58.500 --> 28:59.958
and cleaning up after people.

28:59.958 --> 29:02.708
<i>I would never say
Vacho was right, but he wasn't wrong.</i>

29:02.708 --> 29:04.958
<i>I didn't wanna mop floors my whole life.</i>

29:04.958 --> 29:07.000
<i>I was working hard to get to the top.</i>

29:07.500 --> 29:08.791
<i>And you know who was at the top?</i>

29:08.791 --> 29:09.875
Team Pepsi

29:09.875 --> 29:11.375
<i>That</i> vato <i>right there. Roger Enrico.</i>

29:11.375 --> 29:12.875
PAVING THE WAY TO
COLA WAR VICTORY

29:12.875 --> 29:15.916
<i>He ran PepsiCo,
which ran Frito-Lay, which ran us.</i>

29:15.916 --> 29:17.000
The Pepsi Challenge

29:17.000 --> 29:19.541
