how do we pay rent? Huh?

44:50.250 --> 44:52.958
How do we buy food? How?
How do we survive?

44:52.958 --> 44:54.458
We'll be okay.

44:54.458 --> 44:56.333
God, baby. I can't do this anymore.

44:56.333 --> 44:58.833
- No, no, no, no, no. Hey, hey, hey.
- Oh, my Gosh.

44:59.458 --> 45:00.625
<i>Cálmate.</i>

45:00.625 --> 45:01.791
Breathe.

45:02.916 --> 45:03.916
Three...

45:05.416 --> 45:07.375
- Two!
- Two!

45:09.708 --> 45:11.833
One. Breathe.

45:19.041 --> 45:20.041
Baby...

45:22.250 --> 45:23.583
Vacho found a job for you.

45:23.583 --> 45:26.083
- It's a full-time job.

45:26.083 --> 45:29.166
Why can't you just talk to him?
For me, please.

45:29.958 --> 45:32.208
And then--
And then I will do this for you.

45:34.500 --> 45:35.583
Yeah, okay.

45:36.250 --> 45:37.208
Okay.

45:38.166 --> 45:41.041
- Hey! You eating the product?
-  Sorry.

45:43.250 --> 45:46.458
Clarence, you gotta believe me.
They got potential.

45:46.458 --> 45:48.666
I just need the product to start sampling.

45:49.208 --> 45:50.541
We got to innovate, remember?

45:51.041 --> 45:53.416
We could cover every Dorito,
Frito and Cheeto with this stuff

45:53.416 --> 45:55.583
and get more orders.
More orders means more shifts.

45:55.583 --> 45:58.416
So, Frito-Lay is gonna make them
because the janitor said so?

45:58.416 --> 45:59.833
Now, Mr. Enrico said that--

45:59.833 --> 46:02.750
Roger Enrico?
We're talking about the guys at the top.

46:02.750 --> 46:06.416
You ain't at the top. I ain't at the top.
Those guys up there are.

46:06.416 --> 46:09.958
Wait, sometimes we just gotta
show 'em what the burrito's worth.

46:09.958 --> 46:11.500
What does that even mean, son?

46:11.500 --> 46:15.000
It may look like it's worthless, but
if people just took a bite, they'd see.

46:15.000 --> 46:18.625
Someone took a chance on you, didn't they?
You got on that machine somehow.

46:18.625 --> 46:21.250
If they took a chance on you again,
you'd run this whole damn place.

46:21.250 --> 46:23.583
- Of course I would.
- Because you believe it.

46:23.583 --> 46:25.166
And I believe in this.

46:25.166 --> 46:28.125
And I know it sounds crazy,
but what else is there to do?

46:28.125 --> 46:29.625
Lose our jobs? Go hungry?

46:34.208 --> 46:35.208
You got a point.

46:38.041 --> 46:40.541
Yo, what are you doing?
Eating all the Cheetos?

46:40.541 --> 46:41.958
So I got a plan, <i>carnal</i>.

46:41.958 --> 46:45.250
All right. So I was talking to Clarence.
This is what we're gonna do.

46:46.500 --> 46:48.958
<i>We had it all to gain and nothin' to lose.</i>

46:48.958 --> 46:53.333
<i>We were just a bunch of brown chips
on a conveyor belt, waitin' to get tossed.</i>

46:57.208 --> 46:59.125
- Thank you, brother. All right.

46:59.125 --> 47:00.833
Almost forgot your Cheetos.

47:00.833 --> 47:01.916
Hey.

47:03.333 --> 47:05.000
That's the Doritos, Fritos, Cheetos.

47:05.000 --> 47:08.083
Hey. Don't get your hopes up too high.
Okay, fool?

47:15.166 --> 47:16.500
You kickin' with these fools again?

47:16.500 --> 47:17.583
Tony, let's go!

47:17.583 --> 47:20.041
You take care of your family.
I take care of mine.

47:23.083 --> 47:25.750
<i>Yeah,
Tony had to go back to that drug life.</i>

47:25.750 --> 47:27.375
<i>'Cause his mom was battling cancer,</i>

47:27.375 --> 47:30.375
<i>and he didn't have any money
to pay for doctor bills.</i>

47:31.291 --> 47:34.041
<i>We were all gonna do whatever it takes
to take care of our families.</i>

47:34.625 --> 47:36.000
It's a full-time job, <i>mijo</i>.

47:36.666 --> 47:38.416
That's good. Full-time's good.

47:39.625 --> 47:42.250
Like Pastor Marco said,
after a year, you'll move on up.

47:42.250 --> 47:43.916
- Ain't that right, Pastor?

47:43.916 --> 47:44.833
 Exactly.

47:44.833 --> 47:46.250
-  Hey, boys, come on.
- Ow.

47:46.250 --> 47:49.125
 And it might pay even more.

47:50.041 --> 47:52.500
In a year, you could be
the head of maintenance.

47:53.000 --> 47:56.166
So, I would go from being a janitor

47:57.958 --> 47:59.125
to being a janitor?

48:00.083 --> 48:02.833
And, hopefully,
<i>si me pongo las pilas</i>, and I'm lucky,

48:02.833 --> 48:05.583
I'm gonna maybe be janitor-in-chief?
President of the janitors?

48:05.583 --> 48:08.208
King of the janitors?

48:08.875 --> 48:10.750
Nah, I'm good.

48:11.750 --> 48:15.000
I think I'll stick with Frito-Lay,
where I have a real future.

48:16.791 --> 48:20.083
Better the devil you know
than the devil you don't, eh, Vacho?

48:21.250 --> 48:24.333
Don't be stupid, <i>mijo</i>. They don't believe
in you or care about you.

48:24.333 --> 48:25.416
And you do?

48:26.333 --> 48:28.583
All that ever comes out of your mouth
is what an idiot I am.

48:28.583 --> 48:30.958
That I ain't worth shit.
I can't do nothin' right.

48:30.958 --> 48:33.208
You expect me to trust you
when you say God believes in me?

48:33.208 --> 48:34.625
He does.

48:35.333 --> 48:36.708
According to the Book of Vacho.

48:37.041 --> 48:38.250
 Don't talk to me like that.

48:38.750 --> 48:40.458
You respect me in front of my company--

48:40.458 --> 48:41.541
Respect you?

48:46.166 --> 48:47.500
Hey, check it out, Pastor.

48:48.708 --> 48:51.333
I bet you didn't know that
he beat the shit out of me my whole life.

48:52.291 --> 48:56.583
But it doesn't bother me.
Because I got thick skin and a hard skull.

48:57.333 --> 48:58.833
You know what really sucks, <i>Apá</i>?

48:59.333 --> 49:04.750
Is that I hear your voice in my head,
beating my brain every day.

49:06.166 --> 49:10.375
And for some reason,
that's the beating I can't get up from.

49:12.583 --> 49:14.083
- I'm just trying to help.
- Back off.

49:14.083 --> 49:15.041
Hey, baby.

49:15.041 --> 49:17.875
It's getting so bad, your wife is looking
for help behind your back.

49:17.875 --> 49:20.291
- She's lost all faith in you.
- Hey, hey, hey! Hey, hey, hey!

49:20.291 --> 49:23.041
You do not speak for me, Vacho,
and you sure as hell don't speak for God.

49:24.083 --> 49:27.083
Richard, look at me. I did not say
that I didn't have faith in you.

49:28.041 --> 49:30.375
I know what Richard is,
and I know what he isn't.

49:30.375 --> 49:33.875
Not educated? Sure.
But he is the smartest person that I know.

49:34.916 --> 49:36.750
He already knows God.

49:37.500 --> 49:39.875
You wanna save someone? Save yourself.

49:40.791 --> 49:43.833
And then you come to him
when you're the father that he needs.

49:45.000 --> 49:48.208
Come on, baby.
We're gonna go put my voice in your head.

49:49.500 --> 49:50.958
Come on, kids. We're leaving. Let's go.

49:50.958 --> 49:52.291
I don't want to go.

49:52.291 --> 49:53.625
Come on. Just go.

50:00.083 --> 50:01.583
Let's go, guys. Get in the car.

50:06.416 --> 50:10.125
Hey. If we're gonna make those <i>güeritos</i>
sweat, we're gonna get the good stuff.

50:12.541 --> 50:15.416
<i>To be the best,
you had to get the best. Homegrown, baby.</i>

50:15.416 --> 50:16.500
MEXICO LINDO

50:16.500 --> 50:20.708
<i>Chile molido, chile fresco,
chile guajillo, chile piquín,</i>

50:20.708 --> 50:22.916
<i>I mean, you name it,
we cleared the shelves of it.</i>

50:22.916 --> 50:24.000
Baby, get the red chile.

50:24.000 --> 50:26.125
- I can't, Mom.
- Yes, you can, <i>Papá</i>. Come on.

50:30.291 --> 50:32.125
Jude, which chiles do you want?

50:32.125 --> 50:33.583
All of 'em, babe.

50:33.583 --> 50:35.875
<i>No chile was left unturned.</i>

50:36.625 --> 50:38.875
Jude! Jalapeños or serranos?

50:39.750 --> 50:42.375
Hey, babe! I found some <i>güeritos</i>.

50:42.375 --> 50:46.000
Okay, baby. Which one you wanna try?
The Cheetos? Fritos? Doritos? The popcorn?

50:46.000 --> 50:48.125
<i>And I had my very own focus group.</i>

50:48.125 --> 50:49.750
- Uh, Doritos.
- Oh, yeah.

50:54.416 --> 50:56.458
Hot!

50:56.458 --> 50:58.583
Hot like <i>elote</i> hot? Good hot?

50:58.583 --> 51:00.708
- No! Bad, bad, bad.
- Come on.

51:04.041 --> 51:05.125
- Oh, my-- Baby.
- Hot.

51:05.125 --> 51:06.041
Oh, water!

51:06.041 --> 51:09.125
Chale<i>, man.
That salsa would've made the devil sweat.</i>

51:09.625 --> 51:11.083
<i>While we were trying to remember</i>

51:11.083 --> 51:15.500
<i>everything our</i> abuelitas <i>taught us
about chile, apparently, in the Midwest,</i>

51:15.500 --> 51:18.083
<i>they had already been spicing things up
for a while.</i>

51:18.083 --> 51:21.708
<i>Except their ingredients came
in test tubes and syringes.</i>

51:21.708 --> 51:22.833
Oh, it's hot.

51:22.833 --> 51:25.000
- Hot. Hot. Hot!

51:25.000 --> 51:27.250
<i>I don't know what's going down over there.</i>

51:27.250 --> 51:31.416
<i>All I knew was, our ingredients came
from the ground. Our roots.</i>

51:32.375 --> 51:33.625
Maltodextrin.

51:35.500 --> 51:37.500
Monosodium glutamate.

51:39.500 --> 51:41.916
Disodium inosinate.

51:41.916 --> 51:45.000
<i>Me and Judy had
that spice in our DNA.</i>

51:45.000 --> 51:46.375
You gotta turn the bowl.

51:46.375 --> 51:47.708
- Look, taste this.

51:47.708 --> 51:49.125
There you go. How is it?

51:49.916 --> 51:50.916
- It's wet.
- Wet?

51:50.916 --> 51:53.333
I think we need to bake 'em.
I think they need to be dry ingredients.

51:53.333 --> 51:54.750
Wait, no, no, no. Try it.

51:54.750 --> 51:57.000
- Ah, <i>chile de pasilla</i>.
-  Mmm.

51:57.000 --> 51:59.125
Dad, just shake it. It's not sticking.

51:59.625 --> 52:02.125
It's gotta tumble,
like it does in the factory.

52:07.666 --> 52:12.125
<i>If anyone was gonna crack this recipe,
it was gonna be us: the Montañez.</i>

52:14.083 --> 52:16.875
<i>We had tried every chile
in every store in town.</i>

52:19.250 --> 52:20.250
<i>Until finally...</i>

52:31.041 --> 52:32.708
Ow! Ow! Ow! It burns!

52:32.708 --> 52:34.291
Burns good or burns bad?

52:35.750 --> 52:37.416
It burns good.

52:37.416 --> 52:38.750
- Oh!

52:38.750 --> 52:39.833
Oh, we did it!

52:39.833 --> 52:41.166
- Oh. Yeah!

52:41.166 --> 52:42.500
Of course we did!

52:48.333 --> 52:51.083
I'm just doing
what corporate tells me to do.

52:51.583 --> 52:52.583
What happened?

52:53.250 --> 52:56.250
- Layoffs, son. Lots of 'em.
-  I'm the messenger here.

52:58.333 --> 53:00.000
Where's Tony? Where's Nacho?

53:01.791 --> 53:04.125
Do you really think
I wanna lay people off?

53:04.125 --> 53:07.583
Okay. Hey, hey, hey! That's it!
That's all I got for now, okay?

53:07.583 --> 53:08.875
Back to work.

53:08.875 --> 53:11.041
- Hey, Lonny!
-  Somebody put this ladder back.

53:11.041 --> 53:13.500
Lonny, hold up, man.
Hey, look. You gotta listen to me.

53:13.500 --> 53:16.416
I got an idea.
An idea you gotta tell Enrico about.

53:17.041 --> 53:19.500
It's a new line of products.
It's a spicy chip!

53:19.500 --> 53:22.958
It's gonna change everything.
Spicy Doritos, Fritos, Cheetos.

53:22.958 --> 53:24.041
Spicy what?

53:24.041 --> 53:26.708
I just laid off
a slew of hardworking guys again.

53:26.708 --> 53:28.083
- Yeah--
- A lot of 'em your friends,

53:28.083 --> 53:30.000
and you wanna tell me
about some new flavor you got?

53:30.000 --> 53:31.333
Look, if you just called Enrico...

53:31.333 --> 53:33.166
Oh, you just want me to call Enrico?

53:33.166 --> 53:35.083
- Yeah.
- And just tell him,

53:35.083 --> 53:39.208
"Oh, our janitor, the guy who cleans
the toilets, he's got a bright idea"?

53:39.208 --> 53:41.416
You know I can do more
than clean the toilets, Lonny.

53:41.416 --> 53:43.000
It ain't like that, okay?

53:43.000 --> 53:46.791
New products take years to develop,
cost millions to launch,

53:46.791 --> 53:50.083
and they do not get created
by blue-collar hoodlums,

53:50.083 --> 53:53.083
who probably can't spell
the word "hoodlum."

53:54.583 --> 53:56.541
Hey! What's with the chitchat?

54:03.500 --> 54:04.583
<i>When I was seven,</i>

54:05.666 --> 54:09.000
<i>these white ladies would come
to our school to tutor us in reading.</i>

54:09.791 --> 54:12.291
<i>Except there were two trailers.
One for the white kids...</i>

54:12.291 --> 54:13.583
LONNY MASON
PLANT SUPERVISOR

54:13.583 --> 54:16.416
<i>...and one for everybody else,
the brown kids.</i>

54:17.041 --> 54:20.083
<i>Because, you know,
they liked to keep us separate.</i>

54:21.750 --> 54:23.625
<i>And then,
kids that came out of the white trailer,</i>

54:23.625 --> 54:26.041
<i>they always came out
with cookies in their hands.</i>

54:27.791 --> 54:29.375
<i>And I really wanted one of those cookies.</i>

54:29.375 --> 54:30.541
COMPANY TELEPHONE DIRECTORY

54:32.625 --> 54:34.916
<i>And one day, I got in that line.</i>

54:38.250 --> 54:39.791
<i>The white kids spit at me, shoved me...</i>

54:39.791 --> 54:41.541
FRITO-LAY CORPORATE HEADQUARTERS
EXECUTIVE OFFICES

54:41.541 --> 54:43.166
<i>... and told me, "Go back to Mexico!"</i>

54:43.166 --> 54:44.625
ROGER ENRICO
Chief Executive Officer

54:45.458 --> 54:47.958
<i>But I didn't care. I stayed in that line.</i>

54:49.000 --> 54:50.875
<i>I went into that trailer.</i>

54:54.666 --> 54:58.833
<i>And when I came out,
I came out with my damn cookies.</i>

55:21.625 --> 55:24.333
Patti
Secretary to Roger Enrico

55:25.916 --> 55:27.625
Office of President Roger Enrico.

55:27.625 --> 55:29.333
Uh, hi.

55:29.333 --> 55:32.458
Uh, may I speak with Roger Enrico, please?
This is Richard Montañez.

55:32.458 --> 55:35.125
Uh, what country are you calling from,
Mr. Montañez?

55:35.708 --> 55:36.875
United States.

55:37.875 --> 55:42.166
Well, you're not
the president of American corporate,

55:42.166 --> 55:43.375
'cause that's not his name.

55:43.375 --> 55:44.833
I work in California.

55:44.833 --> 55:46.875
Don't say anything. This says "received."

55:46.875 --> 55:48.833
Oh, you're the VP of California.

55:48.833 --> 55:49.916
<i>No, I, um...</i>

55:49.916 --> 55:52.458
- You. Let's go.
- I work at the Rancho Cucamonga plant.

55:52.458 --> 55:54.541
Okay, so you're the plant director?

55:54.541 --> 55:57.750
Not exactly.
I work "inside" inside the plant.

55:57.750 --> 55:58.833
I'm, uh...

56:01.041 --> 56:02.458
I'm a maintenance technician.

56:05.541 --> 56:06.666
Hello?

56:06.666 --> 56:09.375
Um, the janitor? You're the janitor?

56:09.375 --> 56:11.000
Okay, no, no, don't-don't-don't hang up.

56:11.000 --> 56:13.083
I have an idea that's gonna
revolutionize Frito-Lay.

56:13.083 --> 56:15.041
That'll save our factory,
that'll save jobs,

56:15.041 --> 56:17.583
that'll save hardworking people
who are just trying to survive.

56:18.083 --> 56:21.333
Look, if he cares about his people,
his people on the line,

56:21.333 --> 56:22.916
Mr. Enrico needs to hear this.

56:33.625 --> 56:34.625
Please hold.

56:42.875 --> 56:44.541
Hello, Richard. This is Roger.

56:44.541 --> 56:46.541
Mr. Enrico, uh--

56:48.708 --> 56:50.291
Thank you for taking my call.

56:50.291 --> 56:52.041
I have an idea that you need to hear.

56:52.875 --> 56:54.041
I'm listening.

56:54.041 --> 56:55.791
<i>Okay, yes, sir.</i>

56:55.791 --> 56:59.833
I'm Mexican and proud of it.
And there's a lot of us in this country,

56:59.833 --> 57:02.583
and we spend money on snacks
just like everybody else.

57:03.125 --> 57:06.625
We eat Doritos, but not before
covering them suckers with Tapatio.

57:06.625 --> 57:09.625
<i>It's like the more it burns,
the more money we'll spend on it.</i>

57:09.625 --> 57:12.333
So I thought,
"Why don't I make my own spicy slurry?"

57:12.333 --> 57:15.791
You made your own spicy slurry?

57:15.791 --> 57:17.333
<i>Yeah, I did. And it's good.</i>

57:17.333 --> 57:21.708
You can slather it on everything:
Doritos, Fritos, popcorn, Cheetos.

57:21.708 --> 57:24.875
And the best part, sir,
it is 100% Mexican-approved.

57:24.875 --> 57:28.000
Uh, my family, my neighbors,
they can't get enough.

57:28.000 --> 57:32.000
<i>And I got a plan, Mr. Enrico, to get it
to the streets, to get it to my people.</i>

57:32.000 --> 57:36.291
I think it will save our factory.
It will save jobs.

57:36.875 --> 57:38.000
Save jobs, huh?

57:39.750 --> 57:42.541
That's a lot of confidence there, Richard.

57:42.541 --> 57:49.166
Yes, sir. And you said in the video,
"Think like a CEO." So I did.

57:53.750 --> 57:55.250
You saw my video?

57:55.250 --> 57:56.333
<i>Yes, sir.</i>

57:56.333 --> 57:58.416
And you're a janitor?

57:58.416 --> 57:59.875
Maintenance crew, sir.

57:59.875 --> 58:02.875
Look, if it's okay,
I'd like to send you some samples, sir.

58:04.291 --> 58:07.541
Richard, that's more than okay with me.

58:07.541 --> 58:09.000
-<i>More than okay.</i>

58:09.875 --> 58:10.875
Thank you, sir.

58:15.458 --> 58:16.416
SPICY CHEETOS

58:16.416 --> 58:18.041
-  Next.
- Go, go.

58:18.041 --> 58:20.083
CONTROL CARRIER

58:21.291 --> 58:23.916
What are we doing, guys?
First class? Priority?

58:24.708 --> 58:25.708
Hold on a sec.

58:31.166 --> 58:32.166
We should pray.

58:33.125 --> 58:34.875
- We should?
- Yeah.

58:34.875 --> 58:38.791
I mean, God got us here, right?
We should let God take it home.

58:39.833 --> 58:40.875
Yeah. Yeah.

58:44.625 --> 58:47.791
Uh, dear God, Jesus, señor...

58:48.875 --> 58:50.416
- I mean, you know who you are.

58:50.416 --> 58:55.375
Listen, man. We both know I've--
I've made a lot of mistakes in my life.

58:55.375 --> 58:59.958
Mmm, the gang, the guns, the drugs,
the stolen cars, the other drugs.

59:00.458 --> 59:01.708
Man, there was a lot of drugs.

59:01.708 --> 59:06.083
You know,
maybe I wasn't never bad, just lost.

59:07.000 --> 59:08.541
But I'm doing good things now, so--

59:08.541 --> 59:10.500
What the heck, man? Let's move it.

59:10.500 --> 59:13.375
Hey! He is praying, <i>pendejo</i>!
Have some respect.

59:15.166 --> 59:16.291
Go ahead, baby.

59:16.958 --> 59:21.166
Lord, please forgive me
for all my past sins, and...

59:23.416 --> 59:25.458
pour all your blessings
onto this box right here.

59:27.875 --> 59:28.875
A-Amen?

59:28.875 --> 59:30.375
Amen.

59:32.625 --> 59:33.916
Amen.

59:35.791 --> 59:36.791
Amen.

59:38.500 --> 59:39.458
OVERNIGHT MAIL

59:40.458 --> 59:41.458
Roger Enrico
President & CEO

59:41.458 --> 59:42.541
Here you go, sir.

59:44.916 --> 59:46.541
SPICY CHEETOS - SPICY DORITOS
SPICY POPCORN

59:46.541 --> 59:49.416
 <i>That Italian jefe
was about to have his mind blown.</i>

59:58.541 --> 59:59.541
Holy!

01:00:00.333 --> 01:00:01.666
Hot! That's h--

01:00:02.291 --> 01:00:03.291
Mama hot!

01:00:04.833 --> 01:00:05.958
Patti!

01:00:06.833 --> 01:00:09.166
Water.

01:00:27.833 --> 01:00:28.833
Maintenance. Richard.

01:00:29.875 --> 01:00:31.500
Richard, it's Roger.

01:00:31.500 --> 01:00:32.875
<i>Roger Enrico.</i>

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:35.375
-<i>Are you there?</i>
- Yes, sir.

01:00:35.875 --> 01:00:39.583
